				%h4 Insa-dong for last-minute souvenir shopping 
				%p Most people say a trip to Seoul isn’t complete without a quick stroll down Insa-dong, a long traditional boulevard filled with Korean tea houses, restaurants, galleries and souvenir shops. While that might sound appealing, keep in mind the area is quite touristy and busy—especially on weekends. We’ve made Insa-dong the last priority on your list. After all, by now, you will already have traversed the streets of Samcheong-dong, a traditional experience that’s preferred by locals.
				%span.label Tip
				%p
					%em Instead of walking in through the main entrance where the tourist information booth is located, enter through another opening immediately off Anguk Station, exit 6 (it’s so narrow, it looks more like a gap than a road). Take this labyrinth filled with tiny restaurants and tea shops into the heart of Insa-dong.
